### Good Code Snippet
```java
import java.io.File;
import java.io.FileNotFoundException;
import java.util.Scanner;

public class SecureFileExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Get user input for file path (with validation)
        Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);
        System.out.println("Enter file name (only letters and numbers):");
        String fileName = scanner.nextLine();

        // Validate and sanitize input
        if (fileName.matches("[a-zA-Z0-9]+")) {
            try {
                // Use a secure way to read file
                File file = new File("uploads", fileName); // Assuming uploads directory is secure
                Scanner fileScanner = new Scanner(file);
                while (fileScanner.hasNextLine()) {
                    System.out.println(fileScanner.nextLine());
                }
                fileScanner.close();
            } catch (FileNotFoundException e) {
                System.out.println("File not found.");
            }
        } else {
            System.out.println("Invalid file name.");
        }
    }
}
```
In the improved code snippet, input validation is added to ensure the file name only contains letters and numbers. Additionally, the file path is made more secure by limiting it to a specific directory (`uploads`), which helps prevent path traversal attacks. This approach significantly reduces the risk of vulnerabilities.

